            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Freshness is a Google ranking signal that favors recently published or updated content. It is most powerful for queries where users expect current information: news, sports results, software release notes, pricing pages, and annual roundups. For evergreen content, freshness matters less than depth and authority.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does updating content help SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>Yes, for queries where freshness is a ranking factor. Updating a page with new statistics, current examples, and a revised publication date can recover rankings that have drifted due to age. The update needs to be substantive — changing the date without updating content does not consistently work.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">What is Query Deserves Freshness (QDF)?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>QDF is Google's algorithm that detects queries with a surge in search volume — indicating users are looking for current information about a recent event — and temporarily boosts recently published pages. Introduced conceptually in 2007 and rolled into the algorithm update in 2011, it is most visible for news events, product launches, and trending topics.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">How often should I update my content for SEO?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>For freshness-sensitive content (news, industry roundups, software docs, pricing): update as soon as information changes. For evergreen content: review quarterly and update if accuracy has drifted or newer examples are available. Monthly review of your highest-traffic pages is a strong baseline practice.</p></div></div>
          </div>
          <div class="faq-item">
            <button class="faq-q" onclick="toggleFaq(this)">
              <span class="faq-q-text">Does freshness affect all pages equally?</span>
              <span class="faq-toggle"><svg viewBox="0 0 12 12"><path d="M6 1v10M1 6h10" stroke="currentColor" stroke-width="2"/></svg></span>
            </button>
            <div class="faq-a"><div class="faq-a-inner"><p>No. Time-sensitive queries (news, sports, events), frequently-changing queries (best tools, pricing, software versions), and recurring queries (annual reports, seasonal events) benefit most. Evergreen queries (how does X work, what is Y) are less affected by freshness signals.</p></div></div>
          </div>
        </div>

